# .NET 8 Migration: BackgroundProcessor

## Key Breaking Changes

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | **Removed entirely** |
| `ThreadAbortException` | **Never thrown by runtime** |
| Manual `Thread` + `volatile bool` | Use `CancellationToken` + `Task` |

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IAsyncDisposable
{
    private Task? _workerTask;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerTask = Task.Run(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                // Pass the token so blocking calls become cancellable
                var item = await GetNextItemAsync(token);
                await ProcessItemAsync(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Graceful shutdown requested — replaces ThreadAbortException
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break; // exit loop cleanly; finally still runs
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public async Task StopAsync(TimeSpan? timeout = null)
    {
        if (_cts is null || _workerTask is null)
            return;

        // Signal cancellation (replaces _running = false + Thread.Abort)
        await _cts.CancelAsync();

        // Wait with a timeout instead of Thread.Sleep + Abort
        var effectiveTimeout = timeout ?? TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5);
        if (_workerTask != await Task.WhenAny(_workerTask, Task.Delay(effectiveTimeout)))
        {
            // Log warning — task did not complete in time.
            // There is NO forced-kill equivalent in .NET 8. You must
            // ensure all blocking calls respect the CancellationToken.
        }
    }

    public async ValueTask DisposeAsync()
    {
        await StopAsync();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

## Critical Pitfalls

**1. No forced termination exists in .NET 8.**
`Thread.Abort()` has no replacement. Every blocking call (`GetNextItem`, DB queries, HTTP calls, `BlockingCollection.Take`) **must** accept a `CancellationToken` or you'll hang on shutdown:

```csharp
// ❌ Will block forever, ignoring cancellation
var item = queue.Take();

// ✅ Throws OperationCanceledException on cancel
var item = queue.Take(token);
```

**2. `ThreadAbortException` catch blocks become dead code.**
They compile but never execute. Replace with `OperationCanceledException`:

```csharp
// ❌ Dead code in .NET 8 — never caught
catch (ThreadAbortException) { ... }

// ✅ Catches cancellation
catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested) { ... }
```

**3. `Thread.ResetAbort()` throws at runtime.**
Any call to it will throw `PlatformNotSupportedException`. Remove it entirely — `OperationCanceledException` doesn't auto-rethrow, so no reset is needed.

**4. `volatile bool` is a race condition.**
It can't wake a blocked thread. `CancellationToken` cooperates with `async` APIs and `WaitHandle`-based waits, unblocking them immediately.

**5. For hosted apps, prefer `BackgroundService`:**

```csharp
public class Processor : BackgroundService
{
    protected override async Task ExecuteAsync(CancellationToken stoppingToken)
    {
        while (!stoppingToken.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            var item = await GetNextItemAsync(stoppingToken);
            await ProcessItemAsync(item, stoppingToken);
        }
    }
}

// Registration:
builder.Services.AddHostedService<Processor>();
```

This integrates with the host lifecycle — graceful shutdown, health checks, and DI come free.
